'''Charles Lee''' is an American [[environmental justice]] activist and the senior policy advisor in the Office of Environmental Justice at the [[Environmental Protection Agency]].<ref name=mfn>{{Cite news |url=http://www.movingforwardnetwork.com/2017/04/environmental-justice-leader-charles-lee-honored-by-the-state-of-south-carolina/ |title=Environmental justice leader Charles Lee honored by the State of South Carolina |date=2017-04-04 |work=Moving Forward Network |access-date=2017-10-07 |language=en-US}}</ref> Previously, he served as the director of the Office of Environmental Justice,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://grist.org/climate-energy/heres-the-history-of-environmental-justice-summed-up-in-less-than-4-minutes/ |title=Here’s the history of environmental justice, summed up in less than 4 minutes |date=2014-08-05 |work=Grist |access-date=2017-10-07 |language=en-US}}</ref> and before that, he was the director of the Environmental Justice Program at the [[United Church of Christ]] for 15 years.<ref name=ajph>{{Cite journal |last=Morrison |first=Dianne See |date=2009-11-01 |title=Rallying Point: Charles Lee's Long-Standing Career in Environmental Justice |journal=American Journal of Public Health |volume=99 |issue=Suppl 3 |pages=S508–S510 |doi=10.2105/AJPH.2009.178590 |issn=0090-0036 |pmc=2774201 |pmid=19890149}}</ref>
In 1987, the United Church of Christ released a report entitled ''Toxic Wastes and Race in the United States'', of which Lee was the principal author. The report has been described as "groundbreaking"<ref name=mfn/> and as "the first report to use rigorous analysis and methods to show how pollution and environmental hazards were disproportionately affecting minority and low-income communities."<ref name=ajph/> It had a much more rapid impact than Lee had anticipated: within six years, all of its recommendations had been implemented.<ref name=ajph/>
