'''Hornfels''' is an unusual and relatively rare stone used in making [[Lithic flake|flaked stone tools]], and which is found in [[Australian archaeology|Aboriginal archaeological sites]] in [[Victoria, Australia]].<ref>A Record In Stone: The Study Of Australia's Flaked Stone Artefacts By Simon Holdaway, Nicola Stern</ref> A sample of places where it has been found can be seen in the geographic section below.<ref>Archaeological survey of Aboriginal chert hornfels quarry sites in eastern Tasmania: a report for the Australian Heritage Commission / David Rhodes, Ian Thomas, Melbourne, Vic. Du Cros and Associates, 1994</ref>

The term has been used for ''...a group of compact, fine-grained, metamorphic rocks that form as a result of contact between sedimentary country rocks and a magma intrusion''. The mineral composition is variable, but commonly contains mica and pyroxene while porphyroblasts of pyroxene, cordierite or andulusite also develop. Sedimentary structures are rarely evident due to a high degree of recrystallisation.<ref>[http://www.ntepa.nt.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0017/20069/vichwaysupparchp2.pdfAdditional Archaeological Survey of Gravel Search Area Victoria Highway]</ref>

