[[File:Presentation copy signed by the author.jpg|thumb|Presentation copy signed by the author]] A '''presentation copy''' is a copy of a [[book]] that has been dedicated, illustrated, or signed (without request) by the author, or a book that was a gift from the author.<ref>{{cite book|last=Carter|first=John|title=ABC for Book Collectors|year=1995|publisher=Oak Knoll Press|url=http://www.ilab.org/eng/documentation/29-abc_for_book_collectors.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Glossary of Book Terms|url=http://www.abebooks.com/books/RareBooks/collecting-guide/understanding-rare-books/glossary.shtml#P|publisher=AbeBooks|accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=OED Online|year=June 2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|url=http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/150685?redirectedFrom=presentation+copy|accessdate=6 August 2013|chapter=presentation, n.}}</ref> An [[inscribed copy]], by contrast, is one signed by the author at the book owner's request. Presentation copies are generally more valuable and rarer than inscribed copies.
==Examples of presentation copies== * [http://collation.folger.edu/2012/01/a-newly-uncovered-presentation-copy-by-margaret-cavendish/ ''Plays, Never Before Printed'' (1668)], signed by [[Margaret Cavendish]] at the [[Folger Shakespeare Library]] * [https://archive.org/details/accountofabipone18221dobr ''An Account of the Abipones'' (1784)], presentation copy from [[John Carter Brown]] to John R. Bartlett at the John Hay Library, [[Brown University]] * [http://brbl-dl.library.yale.edu/vufind/Record/3526234 ''A Study in Scarlet'' (1887)], signed "With the Author's Compliments" by [[Arthur Conan Doyle]] at the [[Beinecke Library]], [[Yale University]] * [http://www.sothebys.com/en/auctions/ecatalogue/2012/english-literature-history-childrens-books-and-illustrations/lot.129.html ''The Nursery "Alice"'' (1889)], dedicated by [[Lewis Carroll]], sold by [[Sotheby's]] in 2012 for £36,050
